    <text>
        <body>
            <head>177. Memorandum From Ambassador-at-Large <persName corresp="recCAUUmNdxvAWExm"
                    >Rowny</persName> to the President’s Assistant for National Security Affairs
                    (<persName corresp="rech6OQ6N5EdBVhDo">Carlucci</persName>)<note n="1"
                    place="foot" type="source" xml:id="d177fn1">Source: <orgName
                        corresp="recft7WGb7Fww0wma">National Security Council</orgName>, National
                    Security Council Institutional Files, SR Box 094, NSDD 256. Secret. Copied to
                    Shultz.</note>
            </head>
            <opener>
                <dateline rendition="simple_right #right">
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1987-01-09"
                        >January 9, 1987</date>
                </dateline>
            </opener>
            <list type="subject">
                <head>SUBJECT</head>
                <item>Ban on Mobile <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1"><rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P"
                            type="topic">ICBMs</rs></gloss> in <gloss target="#t_START_1"
                        >START</gloss>
                </item>
            </list>
            <p>I believe our current position in <gloss target="#t_START_1">START</gloss> banning
                mobile <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1"><rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic"
                        >ICBMs</rs></gloss> should remain unchanged for the time being. The basic
                objective at this point is to obtain Soviet agreement to effective <rs
                    corresp="recvMEtDFpnXkyj45" type="topic">verification</rs> provisions for mobile
                    <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1"><rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic"
                        >ICBMs</rs></gloss>. Retention of the ban on mobiles will provide us with a
                great deal of leverage in negotiating these provisions. Altering our position to
                allow a limited mobile <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1"><rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P"
                        type="topic">ICBM</rs></gloss> deployment under certain conditions, as
                suggested by some agencies, would eliminate that leverage. It would tell the Soviets
                that we would be permitting mobiles prior to any agreement on <rs
                    corresp="recvMEtDFpnXkyj45" type="topic">verification</rs> provisions.</p>
        </body>
    </text>
